On Sunday April 27, 2003, the Tank Barge '''Bouchard No. 120''' struck rocks south of [[Westport, Massachusetts]].  This resulted in a puncture of the barge's hull about twelve feet in length.  As a result, the cargo of the barge, number 6 fuel oil, spilled into the waters of [[Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts]].  While the spill was much smaller than many [[oil spills]], the environmental impacts were felt for years. Estimates of the total amount spilled range from 22,000 to 98,000 gallons of oil according to a publication by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://response.restoration.noaa.gov/book_shelf/1289_ARD_Bouchard_1pager.pdf |title=Buzzards Bay Oil Spill in Massachusetts |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref>

This spill was quite different from some of the more widely known spills like [[Deepwater Horizon]], not just because of its smaller scale, but due to the type of spill that it was. Deepwater, being a spill of oil directly from the ground was pure oil. Bouchard No. 120 contained number 6 [[fuel oil|Fuel_Oil]]. A local scientist from [[Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution|Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute]] explains that the processing of oil yields various components of varying danger to the environment.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eldred |first=Rich |url=http://www.wickedlocal.com/bourne/local_news/x746872607 |title=Old oil spills keep on giving |location=Bourne, MA - |work=The Bourne Courier |date=2006-12-14 |accessdate=2010-06-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702083423/http://www.wickedlocal.com/bourne/local_news/x746872607 |archivedate=2010-07-02 |df= }}</ref>

[[NOAA]] is heavily involved in environmental cleanups of oil spills as well as other damage to wildlife and coastal environments in the [[United States]] largely through their Damage Assessment Remediation and Recovery Program [[DARRP]]. efforts lasted in earnest for several years and continued to some degree until 2007 according to a report by the Buzzards Bay National Estuary Program.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dr. Joe |last=Costa |url=http://www.buzzardsbay.org/oilspill-status.htm |title=Buzzards Bay Oil Spill Cleanup Status |publisher=Buzzards Bay National Estuary Program |date= |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref>

