'''John Cain Carter''' (born 1966 in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]]) is a [[cattle rancher]] and [[Conservation movement|conservationist]] who started the [[Brazil]]ian [[rainforest]] [[Conservation movement|conservation]] [[non-governmental organization|organization]], [[Aliança da Terra]].<ref name=beef>{{Citation | last = Peck | first = Clint, ''Beef Magazine'' | title = Envirobeef | url=http://beefmagazine.com/mag/beef_envirobeef/index.html | accessdate = 2008-10-07 }}</ref><ref name=mongabay>{{Citation | last = Butler | first = Tina, ''Mongabay.com'' | title = Saving the Amazon Rainforest Through Agricultural Certification | url=http://news.mongabay.com/2005/0604-tina_butler.html | accessdate = 2008-10-07 }}</ref><ref name=mongabay2>{{Citation |last = Butler |first = Rhett, ''Mongabay.com'' |title = Can cattle ranchers and soy farmers save the Amazon rainforest? |url = http://news.mongabay.com/2007/0607-carter_interview.html |accessdate = 2010-01-30 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100107042418/http://news.mongabay.com/2007/0607-carter_interview.html |archivedate = 2010-01-07 |df = }}</ref> Carter moved to Brazil from [[Texas]] in 1996, where he and his wife managed a 8200 hectare cattle ranch between the [[Xingu River|Xingu]] and [[Araguaia River|Amazon]] Rivers in the Brazilian state of [[Mato Grosso]].<ref name=economist>{{cite news |last=The Economist |first= |title=The Amazon's Texan Saviour |pages= |publisher=[[The Economist]] |date=2005-05-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110221734/http://www.environnement-propriete.org/english/documentation/doc/The_Amazon_s_Texan_saviour.pdf |url=http://www.environnement-propriete.org/english/documentation/doc/The_Amazon_s_Texan_saviour.pdf |archive-date=2007-11-10 |dead-url=yes |accessdate=2008-10-07 |df= }}</ref> Shocked by the rapid [[Deforestation in Brazil|deforestation]] occurring in the [[Amazon Rainforest]], Carter started Aliança da Terra to provide [[Incentive|economic incentives]] for [[farmers]] and [[ranchers]] to preserve the forest land.<ref name=mongabay/>
