The '''Manuel Piar Hydroelectric Power Plant''' ('''Tocoma Dam''') is under construction and it is the last [[hydroelectric]] development project in the Lower [[Caroní River]] Basin of [[Venezuela]]. The project includes the installation of {{convert|2320|MW}} [[Megawatt|MW]] to generate an annual average energy of {{convert|12,100|GWh}}. Ten Kaplan generator units, of {{convert|230|MW}}, manufactured by Argentinian company IMPSA, were predicted to begin operations between 2012 and 2014.<ref>{{cite report |title=VE-L1026: Manuel Piar (Tocoma) Dam Supplemental Financing |work=Inter-American Development Bank |url=http://www.iadb.org/en/projects/project-description-title,1303.html?id=VE-L1003}}</ref> The first generator was installed but not yet commissioned in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMPSA installed the first 232 MW Kaplan turbine at the Tocoma Hydropower Plant |url=http://www.impsa.com/en/news/SitePages/23-04-12.aspx |publisher=IMPSA |accessdate=30 January 2014|date=23 April 2012}}</ref> Behind scheduled, the dam began to impound its reservoir on 16 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Venezuela president Maduro oversees filling of Tocoma dam reservoir|url=http://www.salini-impregilo.com/en/press/news-events/venezuela-president-maduro-oversees-filling-of-tocoma-dam-reservoir.html|publisher=Salini Impregilo|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> These units had the world record as of 2012 in power generation at nominal head for Kaplan turbines. The diameter of the runner is {{convert|8.6|m}} and nominal head is {{convert|34.65|m}} with claimed output up to {{convert|232|MW}}.<ref>{{cite report |title=hydropower project Tocoma|work=IMPSA|url=http://www.impsa.com/en/downloads/HYDRO/TOCOMA.pdf}}</ref>

